      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">http://tinyurl.com/nzeuhxo ¶ The image is poor ¶  ¶ in one version and creased in another. ¶  ¶ so transcription is a composite, with the best source cited. ¶  ¶ Both have Bnumbers ¶  ¶ This ¶  ¶ ough...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="Progressnote"
               style="font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; color: #0000FF; hyphenate: false; break-before: page; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'A dangerous poison plant',<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Kerang times</seg>, 19 November 1895, p. [2] (B95.11.05). It is introduced by:</p>
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mr St. Eloy D'Alton, who is ever<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>on the alert for something new in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>botany, says the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Nhill Mail</seg>, surmising that a species which came under<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>his<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>observation the other day was of a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>poisonous nature, sent a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>specimen<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of it to Baron<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Von Mueller. The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>plant, which was discovered in a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>garden near Lemon Spring, about<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>five miles from Mortat, is something<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>like a lily, and attains to a height of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>about 18 inches. It has grassy leaves<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>like an onion, and bears a flower of a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>color between orange and red. The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>plant is said to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>be spreading near<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Melbourne. Baron von Mueller in a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>letter to Mr D'Alton, writes of it as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>follows :—‘.</p>
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Both<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">the Kerang times</seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Nhill<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">mail<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>were published semi-weekly, and the letter is dated to early November on the assumption that<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>D'Alton reported it to the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Nhill mail</seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>soon after it was received.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <ref target="http://tinyurl.com/nzeuhxo">
                  <seg rend="Hyperlink" style="color: #0000FF; ">http://tinyurl.com/nzeuhxo</seg>
               </ref>
            </p>
            <p rend="Progressnote"
               style="font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; color: #0000FF; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">The image is poor<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in one version and creased in another.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>so transcription is a composite, with the best source cited.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Both have Bnumbers<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>This<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>ought to be<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>sourced from<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Nhill Mail</seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>from SLV (not on TROVE)<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as the original source, with the fn altered appropriately. it will need a Bnumber.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="Progressnote"
               style="font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; color: #0000FF; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">SLV cat record at http://search.slv.vic.gov.au/permalink/f/1cl35st/SLV_VOYAGER3531635</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="Progressnote"
               style="font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; color: #0000FF; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">irradeceous</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="3"/>sic in this version, too faint to read in the other</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="Progressnote"
               style="font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; color: #0000FF; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont"
                    style="font-style: italic; background-color: #FFFF00; ">Homer</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont"
                    style="font-style: italic; background-color: #FFFF00; ">i</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont"
                    style="font-style: italic; background-color: #FFFF00; ">a</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Homera<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">in Kerang version, correct in Horsham text</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="Progressnote"
               style="font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; color: #0000FF; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">bulbilles</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>sic in both texts</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.11.00c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To St<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Eloy D'Alton</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>irradeceous<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Typesetter's error for</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>iridaceous?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>plant<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>sent<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>by you<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is as you<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>surmised,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>D'Alton's letter not found.</p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">I toyed with making an entry in the items not found part of M pubs, but decided as we will be able to find it, I will wait until that is done before emending the file. If nothing else turns up in the meantime, it is likely to be allocated B95.11.08, and cross referenced to the other two assuming my added dating statement ¶ to fn 1 is correct, but I would not be surprised if the letter in the Nhill Times was in late October, in which case we would have to redate the letter, M does not seem to have kept the specimen, as it is not on AVH for MEL, under that name or its current name of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <ref target="http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/kew-323388">
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink"
                                style="color: #0000FF; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; background-color: #FFFF00; ">Moraea</seg>
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink"
                                style="color: #0000FF; font-weight: bold; background-color: #FFFF00; ">
                              <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                           </seg>
                           <seg rend="Hyperlink"
                                style="color: #0000FF; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; background-color: #FFFF00; ">miniata</seg>
                        </ref>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(unless it is the Moraea ochroleuca, among the 20 specimens recorded from D'Alton 1895, MEL<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont"
                             style="font-weight: bold; background-color: #FFFF00; ">2262918.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="background-color: #FFFF00; ">It would be worth a look to see what M identified this one as when he got it.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Homeria<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>— the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Homeria<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>lineata<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>from South<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Africa, in its narrow-leaved form.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Like the few other<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Homerias<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>this<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>one<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>also is highly poisonous, and in its native localities cases of death of human<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>beings have occurred from eating the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>bulbs. In our colony cattle have<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>perished from browsing on this plant.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>It<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>should be discarded in gardens<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>within winterless zones everywhere<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>now that attention has been directed<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>to this highly pernicious plant, and it<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>should be uprooted wherever it got<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>away from<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>gardens, and be burnt at<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>once.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>greatest danger of this<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>dreadful<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>bulbous<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>plant establishing<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>itself and spreading on our<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>rural lands<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>consists in its producing copious<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>broods<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>bulbilles, not only from the roots,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>but also from the axils of the leaves,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>so that the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Homerias<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>more largely<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>multiply than any bulbous plant<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>among the hundreds of sorts.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>etc,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-variant: small-caps; ">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. Von Mueller</seg>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-variant: small-caps; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Homeria lineata</p>
         </div>
      </body>
